1 Section 3-8-102. A. As used in the Terry Peach North Canadian
2 Watershed Water Restoration Act:
3 1. "Commission" means the Oklahoma Conservation Commission;
4 2. "Harmful woody species" means a tree or shrub species that
5 is rapidly encroaching into adjoining lands and is likely to cause
6 harm to the environment or economy. Harmful woody species include,
7 but are not limited to, Juniperus virginiana (Eastern Redcedar),
8 Juniperus scopulorum (Rocky Mountain juniper), Juniperus monosperma
9 (oneseed juniper) and, Tamarix ramosissima (salt cedar), Juniperus
10 pinchotii (Redberry juniper), Juniper ashei (ashe juniper), and
11 Prosopis glandulosa (honey mesquite); and
12 3. "North Canadian Watershed" means the an area of land in
13 Oklahoma that drains or sheds water into the North Canadian River a
14 waterway or water basin.
15 B. There is hereby created a pilot statewide program to remove
16 or eradicate harmful woody species in the North Canadian Watershed
17 watersheds to be administered by the Oklahoma Conservation
18 Commission. To accomplish the goals listed in this section, the
19 Commission is authorized to use the funds available in the North
20 Canadian Watershed Water Restoration Revolving Fund established in
21 Section 3 of this act Section 3-8-103 of this title. The purpose of
22 the program is to manage and eradicate, where possible, harmful
23 woody species that damage grazing lands, create significant wildfire
24
Req. No. 11599 Page 2

1 risk , reduce wildlife habitat and reduce water flow into the North
2 Canadian River waterways and water basins.
3 C. In administering the pilot program, the Commission shall:
4 1. Cooperate with landowners, state agencies, and other
5 political subdivisions for removal of harmful woody species;
6 2. Measure the density of harmful woody species and estimate
7 water used by those species;
8 3. Create a study using a parallel watershed with no control of
9 harmful woody species;
10 4. Utilize available funds to cost-share with landowners for
11 expenses incurred in the eradication of harmful woody species by
12 prescribed burn, biological controls, mechanical removal, or
13 herbicide applications;
14 5. Develop grant programs with conservation districts, rural
15 fire departments, and prescribe burn associations for resources
16 needed for prescribed burns, mechanical removal, biological control,
17 or herbicide applications on harmful woody species;
18 6. Bring attention to the problems posed by harmful woody
19 species to create awareness, demonstrate value to all stakeholders,
20 and encourage landowners to participate in the program; and
21 7. Have at least two active project areas in the program, one
22 above the Canton Lake dam and one below.
23 D. The Commission is authorized to promulgate any rules and
24 procedures to effectuate the provisions of this section.
